# What is Infrastructure as Code?

Infrastructure as Code (IaC) is a practice where we use machine-readable source code for provisioning and managing cloud infrastructure. 

## Benefits of Infrastructure as Code

1. It allows easier infrastructure management, version control, automation, and consistency in infrastructure deployments.

2. It also reduces the risk of human error.

## CaC vs IaC

Configuration as Code (CaC) and Infrastructure as Code (IaC) are ways to manage infrastructure resources with a focus on different things. IaC helps in provisioning and managing the base infrastructure in the cloud like compute instances, storage, networking, etc. 

CaC helps in setting up the desired environment on the base infrastructure like setting up config and tools on compute servers. CaC basically ensures the environment of the base infrastructure is correctly configured to run the desired applications. 

Example of IaC \- Terraform, AWS Cloudformation

Examples of CaC \- Ansible, Puppet

# Introduction to Terraform

Terraform is an IaC tool designed by Hashicorp for provisioning, updating, and managing infrastructure safely and easily across different cloud providers using a simple code format. It makes it easier to automate, share, and manage your infrastructure.

## Benefits of Terraform

1. Human readable code structure and highly configurable.  
2. Easy to version control.  
3. It helps in automating infrastructure deployments with very little chance of human error.  
4. It ensures consistency of infrastructure and helps in easier rollbacks of infrastructure changes if required.

## Installing Terraform

Terraform is available for various operating systems like Linux, MacOS, and Windows. You can use this reference from the terraform documentation to install terraform on your desired operating system \- 

[Install terraform on MacOS](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install#darwin)

[Install terraform on Windows](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install#windows)

[Install terraform on Linux](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/install#linux)

Once you have installed terraform on your operating system you can verify it using the following command \-

**`terraform -version`**  


If terraform is installed correctly it will show you the version of terraform installed in the output. The output would look something like this screenshot \-

![Terraform Installation](./img/install-terraform.png)

Once your terraform installation is verified you are good to proceed to get your hands dirty with terraform.

## HashiCorp Configuration Language

As we have learned earlier, HashiCorp is the creator of terraform. For writing terraform source code we use a language called HashiCorp Configuration Language (HCL). 

HCL is a blend of a scripting language and a configuration language which provides better readability and makes it suitable for writing configurable code for provisioning infrastructure resources.

HCL is the primary language used for writing terraform templates making it applicable industry-wide for managing infrastructure as code with terraform.

### Basic HCL Syntax

The basic syntax of HCL includes blocks, attributes, and expressions \-

* #### Blocks 

  Blocks are fundamental units that are identified by keywords and enclosed in curl braces. These include units like resource, module, provider, etc.


* #### Attributes 

  Attributes are key-value pairs within blocks, where keys are strings and values can be strings, numbers, or other data types.

* #### Expressions 

  Expressions allow embedding variables, functions, and references to other resources, enabling dynamic configurations.


# Project Setup and Initialization

For initializing a terraform project we use the following command \-

**`terraform init`**

This command initializes the working directory, downloads the required provider plugins, and sets up the backend configuration for storing state files.

Using the init command, you can initialize an empty directory and a directory with pre-existing terraform configurations.

# Terraform Format and Validating

To keep your terraform code clean, readable, and easy to maintain the **format** and **validate** commands are very help full.

`terraform format` helps in automatically formatting your code to the recommended style with best practices. It adjusts indentation, aligns arguments, and sorts blocks and arguments. This command helps maintain code readability and consistency across team projects.

`terraform validate` helps in checking the syntax of the code and internal consistency of configurations. It verifies that the configuration is syntactically valid, references are correct, and attribute names and types are appropriate. This command catches errors early in the development process, before attempting to apply changes to infrastructure.

# Terraform Providers

Providers in Terraform can be understood as plugins that use APIs of various cloud providers to perform the desired functions related to infrastructure provisioning and management.

Various clouds have their provider for Terraform such as AWS, GCP, Azure, etc. These providers require their own configuration including authentication and endpoint details. The **provider** block is used to specify a provider and we can also use multiple providers in a single terraform project depending on the resources we want to provision. The basic understanding of terraform provider can be understood with the following image \-

![Terraform Providers](./img/terraform-providers.png)

## Terraform Registry

Terraform Registry is a centralized repository form to fetch Terraform modules and providers. The registry supports versioning, ensuring consistent deployments, and includes detailed documentation for each module and provider. Users can also publish their modules to the registry, facilitating community collaboration and reuse.

## Configuring Providers

A provider is configured by specifying the required providers in the **provider** block of the terraform configuration file. It includes details such as authentication credentials, region, alias, etc. Providers need to be initialized using the **terraform init** command. We can configure the same providers multiple times using aliases wherever required.

This provider needs to be added to the **required\_providers** block to fetch it for the terraform registry. A provider can be configured as in the screenshot shared below \-

![Terraform Providers Block](./img/tf-providers-code.png)

Here, in the required providers block we have declared the aws provider, the terraform registry as its source, and the version of the provider. The aws provider will be downloaded from the registry where its version needs to be either 3.27 or greater than 3.27 as specified in the configuration.

In the provider block, we have mentioned the provider name and then the details to be used with the provider like the profile which will be used for authentication purposes, and the region in which the provider can provision resources.

We can also configure a provider multiple times using an alias for it to be used with different resources \-

![Terraform Provider Alias](./img/tf-provider-alias.png)

# Terraform Resources

We define **resources** in terraform configuration for provisioning various infrastructure components such as virtual machines, storage, databases, networking, queues, etc. These resources are defined using the **resource** block in terraform which contains other details required for the resource creation as configuration. Below is an example of a basic resource block syntax \-

![Terraform Resource](./img/terraform-resource.png)  
In the resource block, we specify the resource type and the local name of the resource which is used to refer to the resource across the module but it has no meaning outside the module’s scope. 

In the previous screenshot, we are creating a resource of type **“aws\_instance”** with the local name **“app\_server”**. This resource can be referred to across the terraform module with the same local name. Inside the resource body, we have provided the configuration parameters based on which the resource will be created. Some of these parameters are required and some of these are optional depending on the resource type. 

We can check the various parameters of a resource in the terraform registry docs. For example, the parameters for the resource type **“aws\_instance”** can be referenced from the following page \- [https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs/resources/instance](https://registry.terraform.io/providers/hashicorp/aws/latest/docs/resources/instance)

## Meta Arguments

Meta arguments are special arguments in terraform that provide additional functionality beyond the standard resource behavior. Following are the different meta arguments in terraform \-

1. **depends\_on** \- This meta argument helps in adding dependency between resources to ensure that a resource is created, modified, or deleted after its dependent resource to prevent infrastructure issues. For example, you might want to get the VM created after the subnetwork to ensure that your VM has the subnetwork available.

2. **count** \- This meta argument lets you specify the number of instances of a particular resource to create. If you want to create identical resources in the cloud you can set the resource count and it will create multiple resources by dynamically indexing them from 0 to count-1.

3. **for\_each** \- This meta argument also allows you to create multiple identical resources by defining a set or map of values, unlike count which uses simple integer value. This meta-argument is particularly useful for creating resources with unique configurations derived from the keys and values of the set or map. By leveraging for\_each, you can manage collections of resources more efficiently, ensuring each instance can be individually referenced and customized based on its specific key.

**Note: You cannot define count and for\_each together in the same resource block.**

4. **provider** \- We have already discussed the provider meta argument in the earlier section. This argument lets you specify which provider to use for a specific resource. You can declare the provider in the resource block to specify the provider you want to use for provisioning a certain resource.

5. **lifecycle** \- This meta argument is used to customize the behavior of resources during creation, update, and deletion. It contains the following settings \-

	

* create\_before\_destroy \- This ensures a new resource is created before the old one is destroyed.


* prevent\_destroy \- It protects resources from accidental deletion.


* ignore\_changes \- This specifies attributes to ignore while updating, allowing external modifications without triggering terraform changes.


* replace\_triggered\_by \- Replaces the resource when any of the referenced items change. This was added in terraform 1.2.

# Variables in Terraform

Variables in terraform provide flexibility and make it more configurable. We can define variables in the terraform configuration files (.tf) and their values can be assigned using various methods like default values, command line inputs, env variables, or using a .tfvars file. Variables in terraform can support multiple data types namely \- string, number, bool, list, and map. 

## Input Variables

An input variable can be declared using the following syntax \- 

![Terraform Variables Declaration](./img/terraform-variables-declaration.png)  
As in the screenshot above, the variable “ami\_id” is of type string and has a default value which is “ami-abc1234”. It also has description to explain what is the variable being used for. You can access this variable into your terraform resources by var.\<variable\_name\> as shown in the example below \-

![Terraform Variable Usage](./img/terraform-var-usage.png)

### Type Constraints

The type constraints helps in restricting a value of a particular data type to be assigned to a variable. If a type is not defined for the variable it will accept any kind of value. 

The type constraint is helpful when you want only a certaik kind of data to be assigned to the variable which can prevent various kind of errors. For example, you might want to create a variable to store the maximum number of VMs to create in a an environment where you would required the value to be an integer and not any other kind. So you can use the type constraint to restrict the variable to only accept a value of integer type for this usecase.

### Data Types

Following are the different data types for input variable in terraform \-

* **number** \- It represents a numeric value can be assigned to the variable. It can contain a whole number like 15 or a fractional value like 1.23.  
* **string** \- It represents a series of unicode characters can be assigned to the variable. For example, a text like “abcd1234”.  
* **bool** \- It can hold a boolean value (True or False). It is useful in conditional logics.  
* **list** \- It is a sequence of values enclosed in square brackets which can be accessed by their indexes. It can contain multiple values of different types such as \[1, “abc”, True\].  
* **set** \- Its a collection of unique values in an unordered format. Example \- \[“abc”, “def”\]

**Note:** You cannot directly access the items of a set by its index. For accessing the items of a set by index you have to convert it to a list by the tolist() method.

* **map** \- It is a group of key/value pairs. Example \- { a \= “AWS”, b \= “GCP”, c \= “AZURE”}. The keys in a map must be strings. If the key is an identifier it should be quoted (enclosed in “ “). 

### Variables.tf File

While you can define variable anywhere in your terraform code, its a good practice to centralize the variables in a single file named as variables.tf in your terraform codebase. This helps you creating a single reference point for all your variables making it easier to read and maintain. You can declare all your variables in this centralized file with their type constraints, default values, description, etc.

### Variable Arguments

Following are the arguments which you can pass to modify behavior of a variable as per your needs \-

1. **default** \- This adds a default value to the variable which makes the variable optional.  
2. **type** \- This defines the data type of the variable.   
3. **description** \- This is used to provide a description of the variable.  
4. **validation** \- This is used to add a validation logic to the variable for restricting the variable input value according to your condition.  
5. **sensetive** \- This argument tells terraform that the variable contains some sensetive data and it limits its output for better security.  
6. **nullable** \- This helps in sepcifying if the variable’s value can be *null* or not *null*. 

## Local Values

Local Values is a name given to an expression to use it multiple time directly by the name in the terraform module rather than defining the whole expression every time. It is helps in centralizing the value of the expression and we can easily update the value of expression just by updating it in the local values.

Local values are also known as Locals and can be defined using the **locals** block. An example of declaring locals is below \-

![Terraform Local Values](./img/terraform-locals.png)

You can access local values using the **local** argument as follows \-

![Locals usage](./img/terraform-locals-usage.png)

## Environment Variables

Environment variables help modify the default behavior of terraform. We can set various environment variables in Terraform for different purposes. Environment Variables are not mandatory to set in terraform but they can be helpful in various cases such as increasing verbosity, set workspace, log file path, etc. You can refer to the terraform documentation for more on terraform environment variables \- [https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/config/environment-variables](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/cli/config/environment-variables)

# Outputs in Terraform

Outputs help you to return selected values from configurations and modules, making those accessible to other modules and users. Outputs help you to extract out desired values that might be useful to you for certain post infrastructure creation processes. Outputs are accessible after the apply operation.

A good practice is to declare all the output values in a centralized file named as `outputs.tf` for easier readability and maintainability. 

You can declare an output as follows \-

![Terraform Outputs](./img/terraform-output.png)

There might be outputs which can contain sensitive information which you might not want to be displayed openly. You can use the **`sensitive`** argument to mark an output as sensitive. You will still be able to access the output value programmatically.

# Preconditions and Postconditions

`precondition` and `postcondition` blocks are used to create custom rules for resources, data sources, and outputs.

The `condition` argument is required int the precondition and postcondition block. The condition block contains the expression to be fulfilled by the resource, data source, or outputs. A `true` value is returned if the expression is fulfilled, and `false` is returned if its not fulfilled. An *error message* is returned by terraform if the value is **false**. 

Resources and Data sources blocks can contain both **precondition** and **postcondition** blocks inside the **lifecycle** block. A output can only have the **precondition** block.

You can learn more about preconditions and postconditions here \- [https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions/custom-conditions\#preconditions-and-postconditions](https://developer.hashicorp.com/terraform/language/expressions/custom-conditions#preconditions-and-postconditions)

# Infrastructure Deployment

The motive of IaC is to define your infrastructure in the form of source code and then use the same source code to provision the infrastructure. Once your code is ready the next step is to launch your infrastructure with that code.

To deploy your infra with your code follow the steps below \-

1. Run `terraform init` command to initialise your working directory and getting it ready for other terraform actions.  
2. Run `terraform plan` command to plan and review your changes.  
3. Run `terraform apply` command to apply the changes and create your infrastructure.  
   

To make any changes to your infrastructure follow the steps below \-

1. Update your terraform code to include the changes you want to do in your infrastructure.  
2. Run `terraform plan` command to plan and review your changes.  
3. Run `terraform apply` command to apply the changes and create your infrastructure.  
   

If you want to destroy the infrastructure created with your terraform code follow these steps \-

For partial cleanup \-

1. Run `terraform state rm`  command which will show you the resources in the state file. Remove the resources you want to delete from the state file.  
2. Run `terraform apply` command to apply the changes and create your infrastructure.  
   

For full cleanup \-

1. Run `terraform destroy` command to delete all the infrastructure resources.

# State Management

Terraform maintains a state of your infrastructure to keep your infrastructure and configuration in sync. The state is stored in a tfstate file which maps cloud infrastructure resources to the current terraform configuration to determine changes required to keep the configuration and infrastructure on the same level. 

You can define a remote backend such as a S3 bucket for storing this state file which helps in better security and version management of the file when working with a group of different people making changes in the same template.

## State Locking

When multiple people work on the same terraform template there might be chances that some unwanted modifications may be done to the state file that might result in corrupted data of the file which is not ideal.

State locking is a mechanism where terraform accquires a lock on the state file which prevents concurrent modification to the file. When state locking is enables, terraform acquires a lock on the state file before the apply or destroy actions. If the lock is not available, terraform waits for it or the process fails depending on the configuration. 

State locking is automatically supported by many backend types, including S3 with DynamoDB, Azure Blob Storage, and Terraform Cloud. It’s crucial for team environments where multiple users or automation processes might attempt simultaneous changes. While essential for data integrity, it’s important to implement proper lock management to prevent stuck locks from blocking operations.

## Import Existing Resources

There might me situations, where you may have existing resources in the cloud which you would want to include in your terraform state. The `terraform state import` command lets you bring those exisitng resources under terraform management. 

Alternatively, you can also add these resources in your terraform code inside the `import` block and then run plan and apply.

## Versioning

It’s a good practice to maintain multiple version of the state file over the time for faster rollbacks in case of infrastructure issues. Terraform dosen’t provide the support of versioning state files by itself but you can leverage a cloud service like S3 for storing the state file and enable versioning to maintain multiple version of the file.

## Sensitive Data Management

The state file might contain some sensetive informations like passwords, API keys, etc. It’s important to handle such data carefully as it might be vulnerable to security threats and result in a security breach. 

The below approaches might be useful in handling this problem \-

1. Mark variables as sensitive which contain such type of information.  
2. Enable encryption on state file in remote backend.  
3. Strict access control to state files.  
4. Use external secret management systems for storing and fetching secrets.  
   

## Best Practices

Below are few best practices for state files which can help in better management and usage \-

1. Store state files in remote backends with encryption and versioning enabled.  
2. Use state locking to prevent concurrent modification and prevent corruption of data.  
3. Take regular backups of state file.  
4. Don’t store secret data directly in state files. Use a secret management service.  
5. Keep state files separate from your terraform code in version control.  
6. Review state files regulalry for any bad practices or unwanted resources and clean them up.

## Useful Terraform Commands 

## `terraform graph` command creates a graph of resources and their dependencies in DOT format, which can be converted into a visual representation using other tools. It helps in analysis of resources and their dependencies in complex projects.

`terraform show` command creates a human readable view of the current state or saved plan file.

`terraform state list` command shows the list of resources in the current state.

`terraform output` command is used to extract the vale of an output from the terraform state.

`terraform state rm` command is used to remove resources from the terraform state without destroying the actual infrastructure.

`terraform state mv` command is used to move resources within a state file or separate state files.

`-replace` flag in `terraform apply` or `terraform plan` is used to force the replacement of a specific resource by tainting the resources.

`terraform taint` command is used to mark a resource as degraded or damaged, indicating that this resource will be destroyed and recreated during the next apply operation.

`terraform untaint` command removes the taint on a resource marked by terraform taint command.

`terraform state pull` command pulls the state from the remote backend.

`terraform state push` command pushes the state to the remote backend.

`terraform state replace-provider` command updates the provider information in the state file without making any modification in the infrastructure.

`terraform state force-unlock` command is used to manually release a lock on the statefile.

# Terraform Modules

Modules in terraform can be understood as base templates which contains resources and configurations which can be reused across multiple projects or within the same project. 

Modules promote code reusability, maintainability, and consistency in infrastructure deployments. They can accept input variables, produce output values, and be nested within other modules. Modules can be sourced from local directories, version control systems, or public registries.

## Root Module

The root module can be understood as the default module which is in the main working directory of the terraform template. 

## Child Module

A module which is called by other modules is referred to as a child module. 

## Using Published Modules

Published modules can be used by providing the source of the module which can be stored in a version control system or terraform registry.

## Creating a Terraform Module

We can create a terraform module by specifying the configurations with the resources, variables, and outputs in a separate folder. This module can then be used in different projects using the `module` block and providing the module path or url via the `source` argument.

# Terraform Provisioners

Provisioners can run scripts, upload files, or execute other tools on resources after they’re created. Common types include local-exec (runs commands on the machine running Terraform) and remote-exec (runs commands on a remote resource).

They’re often seen as a last resort when native Terraform resources or provider capabilities are insufficient. Best practices suggest using dedicated configuration management tools like Ansible or Chef instead of heavy reliance on provisioners. When used, provisioners should be designed to be idempotent and handle potential failures gracefully.

## Creation Time and Destroy Time Provisioners

Creation-time provisioners are executed post the creation of any resource while the destroy-time provisioners are executed post the destruction of any resource.

## File Provisioner

File provisioner are used to copy files or directories from the machine running Terraform to a newly created resource. It is useful in copying data such as configuration files, startup scripts, project data, etc. to the resource.

## Local-Exec Provisioner

local-exec provisioner in terraform allows the provisioner to run commands on the local machine running terraform.

## Remote-Exec Provisioner

remote-exec provisoner is used to directly run scripts on the remote resource after it has been created.

## Custom Provisoners

Terraform custom provisioners allow developers to extend Terraform’s provisioning capabilities beyond the built-in options. These are created using the Go programming language and the Terraform plugin SDK. Custom provisioners can perform specialized tasks tailored to specific infrastructure needs or organizational requirements. They follow the same lifecycle as built-in provisioners, executing during resource creation or destruction.

# Terraform Scaling

Scaling is important when you terraform codebase and the number of cloud resources grow. There are various techniques that might be useful when trying to optimize terraform operation speed \-

## Splitting State Files 

Splitting the state file includes breaking down a bigger state file into multiple smaller units. This helps in improved performance, reduced risk of state corruption, and enable parallel workflows.

## Parallelism

Terraform parallelism refers to its ability to create, modify, or destroy multiple resources concurrently. By default, Terraform performs operations on up to 10 resource instances simultaneously. This parallel execution can significantly reduce the time required for applying large configurations. The level of parallelism can be adjusted using the \-parallelism flag in Terraform commands or through configuration settings. Increasing parallelism can speed up operations, especially in large infrastructures, but may also increase load on the API endpoints of cloud providers. It’s important to balance parallelism with API rate limits and resource dependencies.
